
<section xml:id="day-1">
  <title>Introduction</title>
  <introduction>
  <p>
    In a letter to Leonhard Euler in 1742, Goldbach made a claim that is now a famous conjecture.
  </p>
  <assemblage><title>Goldbach's Conjecture</title>
      <p> Every even positive integer greater than 2 can be written as a sum of two primes.</p>
  </assemblage>

  <p>For intance, 8 can be written as the sum of 3 and 5, two prime numbers, while 42,016 = 257 + 41759 (one of many pairs of primes that sum to 42,016).
  </p>

  <p>Do you believe the Goldbach conjecture is true or false?  What would convince you that it is false?  What would convince you that it is true?  How many cases would we need to check to become convinced?</p>

  <p>What makes this claim so famous is that it is still unresolved.  The claim has been verified for all evens less than <m>4 \cdot 10^{17}</m> (see <url href="http://sweet.ua.pt/tos/goldbach.html">http://sweet.ua.pt/tos/goldbach.html</url>).  Is this enough to convince you?  Should mathematicians be convinced?  </p>

  <p>The answer to the last question is, simply, <q>no</q>.  The conjecture remains unproven to this day.  The closest result, proved in 1966 by JR Chen, states that all sufficiently large integers are the sum of a prime and the product of at most 2 primes.</p>

  <p>MORE ON WHAT PROOF IS</p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-root2"><statement><p><m>\sqrt{2}</m> is irrational.</p></statement></theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>Assume <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is rational.  Then <me>\sqrt{2} = \frac{p}{q}</me> where <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are integers and have no common factors. It follows that <me> 2 = \frac{p^2}{q^2},</me> so that <m>p^2 = 2q^2</m> from which it follows that <m>p^2</m> is even.</p>
      <p>Now <m>p</m> itself must be even since an odd times an odd is odd.  Thus, <m>p = 2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.  So, <me>p^2 = (2k)^2 = 4k^2.</me>  Since <m>p^2 = 2q^2</m> as well, it follows that <me>2q^2 = 4k^2,</me> or <m>q^2 = 2k^2</m>.  Thus, by similar reasoning, <m>q</m> itself is even.  But if <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are both even, then we contradict our assumption that <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> have no common factors. 
      Thus, <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is not rational.  </p>
    </proof> 

    <example xml:id="ex-prime-gen"><title>Prime Number Generator</title>
    <statement>
    <p>Goal: Find a function <m>f(n)</m> whose domain is nonnegative integers and whose range is some infinite subset of the set of all primes.</p>
    <p>What about <m>f(n)=2n+1</m>?  Well, <m>f(1)=3</m>, which is prime, as are <m>f(2) = 5</m> and <m>f(3)=7</m>, but <m>f(4)=9</m> is not prime.</p>
    <p>How about <m>f(n)=n^2 + n + 41</m>?  One can check (don't take our word for it!) that <m>f(n)</m> is prime for <m>n = 1, 2, \ldots, 10</m>.  In fact, <m>f(11) = 173</m> is also prime.  And now that we try it, <m>f(12)</m> is prime, as is <m>f(13)</m>, <m>f(14)</m>, and <m>f(15)</m>.  Hold on, <m>f(n)</m> is prime for <m>n \leq 40</m>!! Have we found a prime number generator?  Are you convinced?  No?  Well, <m>f(41) = </m></p>
