<exercises> <title>Exercises</title>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p> Assume that the truth-value assignments for each statement are correct.
      <ul>
      <li> All Linfield math students are sleep-deprived. (True) </li>
      <li> All sleep-deprived people are goofy. (True)</li>
      <li> All sleep-deprived people are Linfield math students. (False) </li>
      <li> All Linfield math students are goofy. (True) </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p> Now given these assigned truth-values, determine the validity and soundness of each of the following arguments:</p>
    <p> a. All Linfield math students are sleep-deprived.  All sleep-deprived people are goofy.  Therefore all Linfield math students are goofy. </p>
    <p> b. All Linfield math students are goofy. All sleep-deprived people are goofy. Therefore all Linfield math students are sleep-deprived.</p>
    <p>c. All sleep-deprived people are Linfield math students. All Linfield math students are goofy. Therefore all sleep-deprived people are goofy.</p>
    <p>d.  All sleep-deprived people are goofy.  All Linfield math students are goofy. Therefore All Linfield math students are goofy.</p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p> Assume that the truth-value assignments for the following statements are correct
      <ul>
       <li> All talented people are insightful. (True) </li>
       <li> All talented people are rich. (False)  </li>
       <li> All college students are rich. (False)  </li>
       <li> All college students are talented. (False)  </li>
       <li> All rich people are insightful. (False) </li>
       <li> All college students are insightful. (False) </li>
       <li> All rich people are college students. (False) </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>In each case construct arguments with TWO premises such that:</p>
    <p> a. The argument is valid, but both premises and the conclusion are false.</p>
    <p> b. The argument is valid, but both premises are false, and the conclusion is true.</p>
    <p> c. The argument is valid, one premise is true and one false, and the conclusion is true.</p>
    <p> d. The argument is valid, one premise is true and one false, and the conclusion is false.</p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
